WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.560
So as mentioned, I am Michelle Ware-Ivy, and I am, okay, there we go.

00:00:10.560 --> 00:00:17.460
I am Michelle Ware-Ivy, and I am currently the founder of the Malcolm Orlando Ivy Foundation.

00:00:18.260 --> 00:00:23.240
And joining us today is to be able to talk about the value of early screening.

00:00:23.640 --> 00:00:27.080
I do want to go ahead and say a big, special thank you.

00:00:27.160 --> 00:00:29.360
Thank you to Dr. Sandra Mazzoni.

00:00:29.700 --> 00:00:35.960
She has been excellent in caring for my dear husband, Malcolm Ivy, and she's always been

00:00:35.960 --> 00:00:40.620
quite innovative in thinking about, again, the patient needs and the patient care.

00:00:40.800 --> 00:00:42.500
So Dr. Mazzoni, thank you.

00:00:46.140 --> 00:00:50.740
I stand before you here as a surviving care partner to my husband.

00:00:51.180 --> 00:00:54.500
He was first diagnosed with multiple myeloma in 2020.

00:00:55.180 --> 00:00:59.400
And what you see here on this screen is a brief snippet of a

00:00:59.400 --> 00:01:03.440
article that was published by my company, Thermoficia Scientific,

00:01:04.000 --> 00:01:08.180
that really talked about, again, turning this loss into legacy.

00:01:08.880 --> 00:01:14.520
And what is a big part for me on this is being able to be that voice in order to, again,

00:01:14.680 --> 00:01:20.120
amplify the early screening process that exists for multiple myeloma.

00:01:20.320 --> 00:01:22.520
There isn't one, as you all know quite well.

00:01:23.080 --> 00:01:24.560
So why does this matter?

00:01:24.560 --> 00:01:29.280
This matters because there is a critical unmet need within our community.

00:01:29.400 --> 00:01:35.360
And I'm so happy and encouraged to hear about, you know, what we're doing in the community space.

00:01:35.540 --> 00:01:38.400
But these are data that you know quite well.

00:01:38.800 --> 00:01:46.020
These are, again, for 2026, projected by the American Cancer Society as to the number of

00:01:46.020 --> 00:01:48.800
patients newly diagnosed with multiple myeloma.

00:01:48.980 --> 00:01:53.600
And then, of course, the deadly, devastating act of the mortality rate.

00:01:53.600 --> 00:01:59.120
And with this, we see a significant unmet need within the high-risk community.

00:01:59.400 --> 00:02:05.920
And this is where we want to make a difference as to having a earlier screening process,

00:02:05.920 --> 00:02:11.820
such as we do for colon cancer and breast cancer, to really be able to make a difference.

00:02:11.820 --> 00:02:14.400
Because again, this really exists.

00:02:14.600 --> 00:02:18.480
And it's personally, for me, created an impact.

00:02:18.740 --> 00:02:25.600
So my personal story here is my dear husband, he was a father, he was a grandfather, and

00:02:25.600 --> 00:02:26.580
he was a baby brother.

00:02:26.920 --> 00:02:30.960
And we lived with this silent condition for years without knowing.

00:02:30.960 --> 00:02:38.620
He was very active and he had a balanced diet, but somehow we miss multiple myeloma with

00:02:38.620 --> 00:02:41.820
signs and symptoms because we simply did not know about it.

00:02:42.760 --> 00:02:49.120
So here takes us through the trajectory of being able to see all of the events that happened

00:02:49.120 --> 00:02:54.620
that led up to that emergency room visit that diagnosed him at a stage three.

00:02:55.420 --> 00:02:56.620
Again, I remain grateful.

00:02:56.920 --> 00:03:04.120
To our diagnostic companies that they are able to identify for us now as to finding

00:03:04.120 --> 00:03:06.120
out about MGUS earlier.

00:03:06.120 --> 00:03:12.640
So we're able to be able to detect for multiple myeloma, but also to J&J that then now there

00:03:12.640 --> 00:03:17.200
is that Dazalexa could be used for smothering multiple myeloma.

00:03:17.380 --> 00:03:22.160
So that way it will help delay the time of getting into full-blown multiple myeloma.

00:03:22.880 --> 00:03:26.700
And what you see here again, really uncovers the fact of missing multiple myeloma.

00:03:26.920 --> 00:03:30.640
So it's very important that we understand this condition and why early screening is

00:03:30.640 --> 00:03:32.340
going to be quite important to us.

00:03:33.780 --> 00:03:38.860
And one of the key ways that I, you know, continue to amplify voice and be a voice for

00:03:38.860 --> 00:03:41.660
the voiceless is through Dr. Giselle Cook.

00:03:41.880 --> 00:03:47.740
I am a citizen scientist within her research that she's doing study to have that early

00:03:47.740 --> 00:03:49.840
screening process at Mayo Clinic.

00:03:50.180 --> 00:03:55.580
She's doing this and not only just screening, but she's providing education to the community,

00:03:55.880 --> 00:03:56.820
building that health care system.

00:03:56.820 --> 00:03:56.880
And she's doing this and not only just screening, but she's providing education to the community,

00:03:56.880 --> 00:03:56.900
building that health care system.

00:03:56.920 --> 00:04:04.640
So one person is able to know about it and they extend the knowledge to other people.

00:04:05.120 --> 00:04:10.320
So again, trying to close that gap of that unmet need in order to be able to diagnose

00:04:10.320 --> 00:04:12.580
and find out about this much earlier.

00:04:14.040 --> 00:04:20.060
And finally here, as far as another opportunity for bridging the gap, I, you know, stand before

00:04:20.060 --> 00:04:20.460
you.

00:04:20.580 --> 00:04:26.300
I've been recently to Capitol Hill, being able to share again, my story, requesting

00:04:26.300 --> 00:04:26.880
for prevention.

00:04:26.880 --> 00:04:31.880
Requesting for early detection and being able to be in the community with community

00:04:31.880 --> 00:04:37.560
physicians, and then our community to be able to amplify educational and build health

00:04:37.560 --> 00:04:38.040
literacy.

00:04:38.360 --> 00:04:45.500
And then most importantly here, not a snapshot on the chart is being part of the Ash patient

00:04:45.500 --> 00:04:50.680
collaborative, where I'm able to share my voice to ensure that when we think about research

00:04:50.680 --> 00:04:56.540
and when we think about clinical trials, that we're making it inclusive, that all patients,

00:04:56.840 --> 00:05:01.740
all lives are thought about, all patients are able to receive these treatments and being

00:05:01.740 --> 00:05:05.620
able again, to have that better access for care.

00:05:05.620 --> 00:05:09.800
So in closing, I thank you, I thank you for the work that you're doing.

00:05:09.800 --> 00:05:15.340
I know there's still a lot to be done and, you know, I'm here to partner with you.

00:05:15.340 --> 00:05:20.580
One of us trying to find and be able to diagnose multiple myeloma much early.

00:05:20.580 --> 00:05:25.980
And this shows the progress that we're making in partnership with a community in partnership

00:05:25.980 --> 00:05:26.800
with Well-Extablished.

00:05:26.800 --> 00:05:31.220
Patient Advocacy Group in order to help amplify the voices.

00:05:31.520 --> 00:05:38.340
So in regard to creating a value, my final word is, you know, again, being able to detect

00:05:38.340 --> 00:05:39.120
this earlier.

00:05:39.120 --> 00:05:43.420
So once we have it detected earlier, there are treatments, as you well know, that will

00:05:43.420 --> 00:05:47.020
be able to sustain lives longer and then potentially save lives.

00:05:47.140 --> 00:05:48.400
So thank you for your time.
